# Lab: VLAN Configuration & Inter-VLAN Routing

## Overview

In this lab, I built a segmented network using VLANs to separate traffic between different departments and implemented inter-VLAN routing to 
allow controlled communication between them. This project helped reinforce how VLANs improve network organization, security, and efficiency.

## Objectives

* Create and configure multiple VLANs
* Assign switch ports to specific VLANs
* Configure trunk links between switches
* Implement inter-VLAN routing using a multilayer switch
* Verify connectivity between VLANs

## Network Design

* VLAN 10 – Sales (192.168.10.0/24)
* VLAN 20 – HR (192.168.20.0/24)

Each VLAN was assigned its own subnet and default gateway using Switch Virtual Interfaces (SVIs).

## Configuration Summary

* Created VLANs on the switch
* Assigned access ports to VLAN 10 and VLAN 20
* Configured trunk links to allow multiple VLANs across switches
* Enabled IP routing on the multilayer switch
* Configured SVIs:

  * VLAN 10 → 192.168.10.1
  * VLAN 20 → 192.168.20.1

## Verification

* Devices within the same VLAN successfully communicated
* Inter-VLAN routing was verified by successful pings between VLAN 10 and VLAN 20
* Used commands like:

  * `show vlan brief`
  * `show interfaces trunk`
  * `show ip interface brief`

## Issues Encountered

* VLAN interfaces initially remained down due to no active ports assigned
* Fixed by assigning access ports and ensuring devices were connected and powered on

## Key Takeaways

* VLANs segment broadcast domains and improve network organization
* SVIs act as default gateways for each VLAN
* Inter-VLAN routing requires both active VLANs and IP routing enabled
* Troubleshooting requires verifying both Layer 2 and Layer 3 configurations
